body:
When we run one yolov3 model from customer on TRT EP, an issue was found regarding how to set profile for dynamic shape (sub)graphs.
The model has more than one dynamic shape inputs. When the shape of some inputs changed, current way is to set/update profiles only for the changed inputs. title: Handle missing initializers in allocation planner to fix crashes with DML provider
body:
This addresses crashes in certain models while creation sessions with the DML provider.

The problem is related to an optimization for memory size in which the DML graph partitioner transfers protobuf initializers out of the graph to manage itself.  The presence of the initializer though is needed for the allocation planner to call ProcessDef for that value and initialize “reused_buffer_index".  With that field left initialized to zero, the planner thinks it’s decided to reuse the same buffer for that initializer and for another value at index zero, causing that buffer to be freed too many times / too early.

The fix is to initialize reused_buffer_index to -1 and detect this case, as well as make the allocation planner a bit more brittle.

With this binding support, new `IOBinding` scenarios are now possible. Some highlights are listed below:

- Allow users to allocate memory (and define contents of the memory) in CUDA (Limited to numeric tensors only for now)

title: Downgrade GCC
body:
**Description**: 

In 1.4 release, we used to have three different kind of build environment: 
1. Ubuntu for most of the CI pipelines
2. manylinux(which is based on CentOS) for python packaging pipeline.
3. CentOS6, which is for all the other packaging pipelines other than python.

The second one relies on Red Hat devtoolset, which gives us a much newer compiler version.

Recently, I tried to unify the docker images that were used in our packaging pipelines. I thought I can just use the manylinux one for all the cases. But unfortunately it's not true. The GCC in the manylinux docker image pulls in new openmp symbols, which are not available on Ubuntu 16.04. So, as long as our official builds still depend on openmp, we'll have to use the stock GCC version(4.8.5) instead. 

So this PR is to bring the third image back.

**Description**: Fix conflicting CMake linker flags with contradict those needed by the Windows inbox universal CRT. From @jstoecker:
"When building for release, linker optimization flags (/OPT:*) have been introduced globally for all executables and shared libs in the ORT CMake file. The WAI inbox toolchain doesn't permit this, since they may conflict or override settings already provided in the inbox UCRT msbuild properties. I've added a CMake variable, onnxruntime_DISABLE_LINKER_OPT_FLAGS, which is undefined by default. The WAI root CMake file will define this to disable the conflicting flags, which is identical to how we handle spectre flags."

**Motivation and Context**

- Inbox DLLs need to link against the Universal CRT for security reasons, compliant with requirements for all inbox Windows components.
